        "content": "| Distance (km) | Diffraction loss (dB) |\n| ------------- | --------------------- |\n| 1.0           | 0.0                   |\n| 5             | 15.0                  |\n| 10            | 23.0                  |\n| 15            | 28.0                  |\n| 20            | 32.0                  |\n| 25            | 34.0                  |\n| 30            | 36.0                  |\n| 35            | 37.0                  |\n| 40            | 38.0                  |\n| 45            | 39.0                  |\n| 48            | 42.0                  |\n| 50            | 4.0                   |\n| 55            | 15.0                  |\n| 60            | 22.0                  |\n| 65            | 27.0                  |\n| 70            | 30.0                  |\n| 75            | 33.0                  |\n| 80            | 35.0                  |\n| 87            | 36.0                  |",
        "chart_caption": [],
        "chart_footnote": [],
        "sub_type": "line",
        "bbox": [
            127,
            108,
            841,
            539
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "In the diffraction region the loss increases to 40 dB at 48 kilometers. At this point tropospheric scatter loss enters the equation and the combined loss drops to 4 dB. In an area coverage plot, this discontinuity will produce seemingly contradictory results as shown below. ",
        "bbox": [
            63,
            547,
            898,
            601
        ],
        "page_idx": 1
    },
